15 Article – Tax – General
16 2–120.
17 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
18 INDICATED.
19 (2) “JUSTICE–INVOLVED INDIVIDUAL” MEANS AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS
20 CONVICTED OF OR PLEADS GUILTY TO A CRIME AND IS CURRENTLY SERVING OR,
21 WITHIN THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING 2 YEARS, HAS BEEN RELEASED AFTER
22 SERVING A TERM OF IMPRISONMENT OF AT LEAST 6 MONTHS BUT NOT MORE THAN
23 10 YEARS IN A STATE OR FEDERAL CORRECTIONAL FACILITY.
24 (3) “PROGRAM” MEANS THE INCOME TAX RECONCILIATION
25 PROGRAM.
26 (B) THERE IS AN INCOME TAX RECONCILIATION PROGRAM IN THE STATE
27 THAT IS ADMINISTERED BY THE COMPTROLLER.
28 (C) THE PURPOSE OF THE PROGRAM IS TO ALLOW JUSTICE–INVOLVED
29 INDIVIDUALS WHO ARE UNABLE TO FILE A STATE INCOME TAX RETURN WHILE
30 INCARCERATED TO:

SENATE BILL 295 3
1 (1) SUBJECT TO SUBSECTION (D) OF THIS SECTION, ESTABLISH
2 INSTALLMENT PAYMENT PLANS TO PAY ANY UNPAID INCOME TAX THAT IS DUE FOR
3 ANY TAXABLE YEAR DURING WHICH THE INDIVIDUAL IS INCARCERATED; AND
4 (2) IF APPROVED FOR AN INSTALLMENT PAYMENT PLAN, RECEIVE A
5 WAIVER FOR ANY INTEREST AND PENALTIES THAT ACCRUE ON THE UNPAID INCOME
6 TAX.
7 (D) (1) FOR ANY TAXABLE YEAR THAT BEGINS AFTER DECEMBER 31,
8 2024, BUT BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2030, A JUSTICE–INVOLVED INDIVIDUAL WHO
9 RECEIVES A NOTICE OF ASSESSMENT OF INCOME TAX DUE FOR A TAXABLE YEAR
10 DURING WHICH THE INDIVIDUAL IS INCARCERATED MAY APPLY TO THE
11 COMPTROLLER FOR AN INSTALLMENT PAYMENT PLAN.
12 (2) IF THE COMPTROLLER DETERMINES THAT THE
13 JUSTICE–INVOLVED INDIVIDUAL IS ELIGIBLE TO PARTICIPATE IN THE PROGRAM,
14 THE COMPTROLLER SHALL ESTABLISH AN INSTALLMENT PAYMENT PLAN THAT
15 ALLOWS THE INDIVIDUAL TO PAY THE UNPAID INCOME TAX OVER A PERIOD NOT
16 EXCEEDING 10 YEARS.
17 (3) IF A JUSTICE–INVOLVED INDIVIDUAL IS APPROVED FOR AN
18 INSTALLMENT PAYMENT PLAN UNDER THE PROGRAM, THE COMPTROLLER SHALL
19 WAIVE ANY INTEREST AND PENALTIES THAT ACCRUE ON THE UNPAID INCOME TAX
20 DUE.
21 (E) (1) TO CARRY OUT THE PROGRAM, THE COMPTROLLER SHALL:
22 (I) IN COLLABORATION WITH THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC
23 SAFETY AND CORRECTIONAL SERVICES, DEVELOP AN AWARENESS CAMPAIGN TO
24 INFORM THE PUBLIC AND JUSTICE–INVOLVED INDIVIDUALS ABOUT THE PROGRAM;
25 AND
26 (II) ADOPT REGULATIONS.
27 (2) THE REGULATIONS REQUIRED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1)(II) OF THIS
28 SUBSECTION MAY INCLUDE INCOME LIMITATIONS THAT ESTABLISH ELIGIBILITY
29 FOR THE PROGRAM.
30 (F) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 1, 2026, AND EACH DECEMBER 1
31 THEREAFTER, THE COMPTROLLER SHALL REPORT TO THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY, IN
32 ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, ON THE
33 IMPACT OF THE PROGRAM.

